> This recipe is from HelloFresh.

Bring a large #saucepan{} of @water{} to the boil with a @salt{0.25%tsp} for the rice. When boiling, add the @basmati rice{150%g} and @ground turmeric{0.25%tsp}, cook for ~{12%minutes}. Drain in a #sieve{}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large frying pan{} on high heat. When the oil is hot, add the @British beef mince{240%g} and @North Indian style spice mix{1} and cook until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #wooden spoon{} to break it up as it cooks. Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped) into small pieces. Once the beef has browned, stir the onion into the pan with the beef and cook, stirring, until the onion is starting to soften, ~{3-4%minutes}.

While the onion cooks, halve the @red chilli{0.5}(halved lengthways, deseeded and finely chopped), peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Drain and rinse the @red lentils{100%g} in a sieve. Once the onion has softened, add the curry powder, garlic and half the chilli and remaining @ground turmeric{0.25%tsp} and cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}.

Add the @tomato passata{1} and @water{100%ml} and @chicken stock powder{1} to the pan and stir together. Stir in the lentils, season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}, add a @sugar{pinch} and simmer until thickened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> TIP: Add a splash of water if you feel it needs loosening.

Add the @baby spinach{100%g} a handful at a time and cook until wilted and piping hot, ~{2-3%minutes}. Taste and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} if needed.

Divide the turmeric rice between bowls. Top with the curry and any remaining chilli. Enjoy!

> Step 2 MOD: If you've chosen beef mince instead of lamb mince, add a drizzle of oil to the frying pan in the step above, then cook the beef mince in the same way the step above and the rest of the recipe tells you to cook the lamb mince.